Sorry, no document or report, but I&#39;m happy to answer your questions.  One
thing to remember though is that this is a modified heritrix crawler.  We
decoupled the content persistence from the fetching.  So when I say 4
machines, that&#39;s 4 machines just doing fetching and managing of the crawler
queue&#39;s.  There was a fifth machine (could be a movie title, &quot;The Fifth
Machine&quot; :-)) that handled all the content store.  We have a custom writer
that streams the content to the remote persistence layer.  The persistence
layer compresses the content and writes it to disk.  Internally we have a
gigabit network connecting the servers.  The io on each server is pretty
modest, just a big 750gb SATA drive for the content and a smaller drive for
the o/s.  The o/s runs in its own partition.



Like I said, we hit a slowdown towards the end of a month of crawling.  We
didn&#39;t do adequate monitoring of the servers so can&#39;t say the cause, right
now I&#39;m speculating that the io on the crawl boxes got too slow as the bdb
instances grew large.  I&#39;ve seen this happen on those boxes for big bdb
instances that are not seeing a lot of cache reuse, but that was a different
app so I could well be wrong.



- leo



  _____  

From: archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
[mailto:archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of pilotboy_84
Sent: Friday, June 06, 2008 1:05 PM
To: archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
Subject: [archive-crawler] Re: Crawling 100 million pages



Hy, i would like to ask you something?
Do you have more information about that crawler of 120 million pages.
I would like to know the resources that I need to match your results.
If you had a document or report that could be shared would be very
helpful to me.
Thanks

--- In archive-crawler@ &lt;mailto:archive-crawler%40yahoogroups.com&gt;
yahoogroups.com, &quot;Leo Dagum&quot; &lt;leo_dagum@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; We did 120million pages in march. We&#39;ve somewhat modified heritrix
for our
&gt; purposes but I&#39;m sure you could do it with the release version. 
Basically
&gt; all you need is enough Internet bandwidth, good DNS and multiple crawler
&gt; instances. We have 10Mbit/s and with our set up we saturated that
with 4
&gt; crawler instances running on single cpu dual core Xeon boxes, each
with 8GB
&gt; memory, used 5GB for java heap. Each machine needs a boatload of disk
&gt; space, not just for the content but for checkpoints (which we actually
&gt; turned off since we&#39;ve been unable to restart a big, multi-million page
&gt; crawl from checkpoint, although it works fine for smaller crawls)
and for
&gt; the various BDB instances used by the crawler for queueing uri&#39;s. 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; The crawl rate did slow down for us substantially towards the end of the
&gt; month. I don&#39;t know why, and it&#39;s definitely something we&#39;ll have to
&gt; investigate when we next do a big crawl.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Another possibility for you would be the nutch crawler. Depends on what
&gt; exactly you want from the crawler. Heritrix is very nice as a stand
alone
&gt; crawler used for harvesting pages from the Internet. From the
little I&#39;ve
&gt; seen, nutch is pretty tightly integrated with the nutch indexing/search
&gt; capability, and designed more for continuous crawling. 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; - leo
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
